A. ITSM: Independent Temporal-Spatial Modules
Independent Temporal-Spatial Modules (ITSM) consist of
multiplepredictionmodulesthatleverageIPtopredictmemory
access patterns by tracking both deltas and strides. Traditional
prefetchers typically rely on a unified prediction table that
globally tracks memory access transitions. Such a monolithic
structure is prone to entry conflicts across unrelated data
streams. Specifically, when count-based confidence is used,
locallyfrequentbutgloballyrarepatternsoftenresultinoverly
short-sightedpredictionsandpoorresponsiveness.Additionally,
the unified table structure enforces coarse-grained prefetch
management,whichcanpenalizehighlyaccuratepredictionsin
otherwiseeffectivelocalregions.Furthermore,accessingalarge
unified table suffers from scalability and responsiveness issues
duetosignificantstorageandlookupoverhead.ITSMaddresses
these limitations by employing five monitoring-tables (MTs),
four of which are each dedicated to a distinct delta range, and
oneMTspecificallyfocusesonspatialaccesseswithinaunified
stride range.
Predictions. Figure 3 presents a high-level overview of
